1
00:00:16,079 --> 00:00:17,679
In northwestern Italy,

2
00:00:18,120 --> 00:00:20,399
there is a land surrounded by mountains.

3
00:00:20,920 --> 00:00:23,239
Valle d'Aosta.

4
00:00:23,239 --> 00:00:25,440
Mont Blanc, Matterhorn,

5
00:00:25,719 --> 00:00:26,879
Gran Paradiso,

6
00:00:27,559 --> 00:00:29,480
Those giants of the Alps,

7
00:00:29,879 --> 00:00:32,880
silently witnessing human insignificance and courage.

8
00:00:34,039 --> 00:00:37,320
Fifteen years ago, someone decided to do something crazy.

9
00:00:38,280 --> 00:00:40,960
to cross the giants' territory on foot.

10
00:00:41,719 --> 00:00:42,399
So,

11
00:00:42,399 --> 00:00:44,479
the Tor des Géants was born.

12
00:00:46,960 --> 00:00:47,880
His name is Hai Guai.

13
00:00:48,280 --> 00:00:50,280
He lives in Beijing and loves climbing mountains.

14
00:00:52,320 --> 00:00:54,000
The taller one is Bai Rui.

15
00:00:54,600 --> 00:00:55,600
He's from Northern Ireland.

16
00:00:56,240 --> 00:00:58,039
They met on Strava.

17
00:00:59,119 --> 00:01:00,719
He was also living in Beijing at the time.

18
00:01:01,600 --> 00:01:03,479
After that, almost every weekend,

19
00:01:03,719 --> 00:01:05,359
they went into the mountains together.

20
00:01:07,040 --> 00:01:08,719
Until Bai Rui returned to London.

21
00:01:09,319 --> 00:01:10,799
they each got busy with their own lives,

22
00:01:11,120 --> 00:01:14,120
and it became hard to meet up and climb together.

23
00:01:28,040 --> 00:01:29,120
Until one day,

24
00:01:29,400 --> 00:01:31,079
Hai Guai and Bai Rui decided

25
00:01:31,519 --> 00:01:34,719
to take on the long-awaited Tor des Géants together.

26
00:01:39,040 --> 00:01:41,040
They would cross the Aosta Valley,

27
00:01:41,480 --> 00:01:43,359
covering 330 kilometers together.

28
00:01:44,040 --> 00:01:45,719
And this is where

29
00:01:46,200 --> 00:01:48,280
their story begins.

30
00:02:24,719 --> 00:02:27,280
Yesterday, I did over 4,800 meters.

31
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:28,599
Of elevation gain?

32
00:02:28,599 --> 00:02:29,400
Ah.

33
00:02:29,479 --> 00:02:30,719
In forty-six kilometers.

34
00:02:30,719 --> 00:02:31,680
Ah, forty-six kilometers.

35
00:02:31,680 --> 00:02:32,639
Over 4,800 meters of elevation gain.

36
00:02:33,639 --> 00:02:35,280
Hai Gui said he wasn't preparing for the race,

37
00:02:35,800 --> 00:02:37,800
It was just a regular training day.

38
00:02:38,319 --> 00:02:40,560
But for most people, a daily routine like that,

39
00:02:40,919 --> 00:02:42,400
would be resume-worthy.

40
00:02:43,599 --> 00:02:44,719
Look at these two pairs of shoes.

41
00:02:46,199 --> 00:02:47,879
How many kilometers can one pair of shoes run?

42
00:02:48,719 --> 00:02:49,800
For him, running in the forest,

43
00:02:49,800 --> 00:02:50,919
to him,

44
00:02:51,159 --> 00:02:52,439
is a way of returning to nature

45
00:02:52,560 --> 00:02:53,800
and to himself.

46
00:02:54,719 --> 00:02:55,560
Every weekend,

47
00:02:55,560 --> 00:02:58,599
he heads into the mountains to recharge.

48
00:02:59,319 --> 00:03:02,159
This is where trail runners in Beijing

49
00:03:02,159 --> 00:03:03,400
do their everyday training.

50
00:03:03,520 --> 00:03:05,280
Everyone knows this place well.

51
00:03:05,800 --> 00:03:07,479
When Bai Rui and I were running in Sanfeng,

52
00:03:07,479 --> 00:03:08,719
we talked about whether

53
00:03:09,159 --> 00:03:11,240
we should sign up for a race together.

54
00:03:11,360 --> 00:03:12,560
After he moved back to London,

55
00:03:12,560 --> 00:03:15,199
we knew that chances to explore the mountains together,

56
00:03:15,199 --> 00:03:17,840
would only get rarer.

57
00:03:18,080 --> 00:03:20,599
A race felt like the best way to do it.

58
00:03:21,520 --> 00:03:24,800
I wanted to do a multi-day race.

59
00:03:24,800 --> 00:03:26,919
That way, we could spend a lot of time together.

60
00:03:27,360 --> 00:03:28,879
If we just ran a 100K,

61
00:03:28,879 --> 00:03:29,840
or a hundred-miler,

62
00:03:29,840 --> 00:03:32,719
we probably wouldn't even have time to hang out afterward.

63
00:03:32,840 --> 00:03:34,639
A multi-day race seemed much better.

64
00:03:40,639 --> 00:03:43,400
My name is Tom. I'm originally from Ireland,

65
00:03:43,400 --> 00:03:44,680
but I live in London now.

66
00:03:45,240 --> 00:03:50,280
And London is a big city, far from the mountains.

67
00:03:50,319 --> 00:03:54,520
But every weekend, I get out to the local hills.

68
00:03:55,840 --> 00:03:58,120
We did a few runs together and

69
00:03:58,120 --> 00:04:01,120
quickly realized that our attitudes toward

70
00:04:01,120 --> 00:04:03,039
running and trail running were very similar,

71
00:04:03,039 --> 00:04:08,439
that we both used it as a way to explore the mountains,

72
00:04:08,439 --> 00:04:10,159
to explore the wilderness,

73
00:04:10,159 --> 00:04:14,199
and to discover new paths and new routes.

74
00:04:14,199 --> 00:04:15,319
That sort of thing. Yeah.

75
00:04:15,319 --> 00:04:16,199
We quickly realized

76
00:04:16,199 --> 00:04:18,000
that there was a real connection there.

77
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:21,279
He just took the photo from a slightly different angle.

78
00:04:24,759 --> 00:04:28,120
At the end of January 2021.

79
00:04:29,439 --> 00:04:32,079
Yeah, get to 50 kilometers,

80
00:04:32,319 --> 00:04:35,399
change clothes there. I'll follow if I can.

81
00:04:35,399 --> 00:04:36,480
I don't think I can keep up.

82
00:04:36,480 --> 00:04:38,560
I think Tom is in good shape.

83
00:04:38,560 --> 00:04:40,079
You're better than I am.

84
00:04:40,079 --> 00:04:41,480
A lot of people say that

85
00:04:41,480 --> 00:04:44,279
when you hit 50 or 100 kilometers,

86
00:04:44,279 --> 00:04:47,199
that's when you feel the most tired and the most pain.

87
00:04:47,199 --> 00:04:48,399
Then just walk for a while.

88
00:04:48,399 --> 00:04:50,319
You rarely get the chance

89
00:04:50,319 --> 00:04:52,800
to race in perfect condition.

90
00:04:52,879 --> 00:04:53,800
I think

91
00:04:54,240 --> 00:04:56,000
the essence of ultra running is that

92
00:04:56,000 --> 00:04:57,639
you're definitely going to run into problems.

93
00:04:57,920 --> 00:04:58,720
Then you deal with one problem,

94
00:04:58,720 --> 00:04:59,279
And then

95
00:04:59,279 --> 00:04:59,720
another problem,

96
00:04:59,720 --> 00:05:00,319
and solve it.

97
00:05:00,319 --> 00:05:01,759
Over 300 kilometers,

98
00:05:01,759 --> 00:05:03,759
you're definitely going to face plenty of problems.

99
00:05:04,120 --> 00:05:05,879
Have you looked closely at this?

100
00:05:05,879 --> 00:05:06,759
What?

101
00:05:07,920 --> 00:05:09,600
It's only two kilometers away.

102
00:05:09,600 --> 00:05:14,120
There's a "W".

103
00:05:14,120 --> 00:05:15,160
It's a waypoint.

104
00:05:15,160 --> 00:05:16,920
It's a waypoint, but there's

105
00:05:16,920 --> 00:05:17,759
no aid there.

106
00:05:18,120 --> 00:05:19,560
Okay, um...

107
00:05:19,560 --> 00:05:20,079
Uh, yes.

108
00:05:20,519 --> 00:05:24,279
Aid stations may have some.

109
00:05:24,279 --> 00:05:27,279
It should say refreshment.

110
00:05:27,680 --> 00:05:30,680
No, not aid, refreshment. Refreshment. Okay.

111
00:05:33,079 --> 00:05:33,439
This place...

112
00:05:33,439 --> 00:05:34,600
It looks like The Lord of the Rings.

113
00:05:35,240 --> 00:05:36,120
The Lord of the Rings.

114
00:05:56,839 --> 00:06:00,519
6, 5, 4

115
00:06:00,720 --> 00:06:03,959
3, 2, 1

116
00:06:03,959 --> 00:06:05,720
Go.

117
00:06:23,920 --> 00:06:25,759
Before starting the race,

118
00:06:25,759 --> 00:06:29,199
I didn't really understand what 330 kilometers meant.

119
00:06:29,199 --> 00:06:32,920
I knew it was much longer than anything I'd run before,

120
00:06:32,920 --> 00:06:34,199
but it was still hard to

121
00:06:34,199 --> 00:06:37,120
fully comprehend what that would feel like.

122
00:06:38,319 --> 00:06:38,920
It wasn't like

123
00:06:38,920 --> 00:06:41,319
I'd run during the day and sleep at night.

124
00:06:41,319 --> 00:06:42,120
Some days,

125
00:06:42,120 --> 00:06:46,079
I'd sleep for an hour or two in the early morning,

126
00:06:46,079 --> 00:06:49,519
or a bit in the middle of the day, and then keep going.

127
00:06:55,319 --> 00:06:57,439
In a way, it's like being a student

128
00:06:57,439 --> 00:06:59,560
who has done a lot of practice questions.

129
00:06:59,560 --> 00:07:01,639
When you face something

130
00:07:01,639 --> 00:07:02,759
like the Tor des Géants,

131
00:07:02,759 --> 00:07:04,319
it may be a new exam,

132
00:07:04,480 --> 00:07:07,920
but it just takes everything you've learned

133
00:07:07,920 --> 00:07:09,519
and rearranges it.

134
00:07:10,160 --> 00:07:12,199
When you face those things again,

135
00:07:12,199 --> 00:07:14,240
you may not even have

136
00:07:14,240 --> 00:07:15,600
the pain you were talking about.

137
00:07:15,639 --> 00:07:17,160
Sometimes you might even feel

138
00:07:17,160 --> 00:07:18,399
a little happy to see the question.

139
00:07:32,319 --> 00:07:35,480
Where's Bai Rui... Tom?

140
00:07:35,480 --> 00:07:36,560
Bai Rui should be behind us.

141
00:08:42,840 --> 00:08:45,320
His bib is 63, and mine is 64.

142
00:08:45,639 --> 00:08:46,679
I didn't expect that.

143
00:08:46,679 --> 00:08:47,399
Are you cold?

144
00:08:47,399 --> 00:08:49,399
It's okay. I've been keeping warm.

145
00:08:57,120 --> 00:09:00,840
Are you okay? Are you cold?

146
00:09:00,840 --> 00:09:01,679
I'm okay.

147
00:09:49,639 --> 00:09:51,399
Water.

148
00:09:55,399 --> 00:09:58,799
To the challenges ahead.

149
00:09:59,120 --> 00:10:03,039
Another surprising thing is how little sleep you actually need.

150
00:10:03,039 --> 00:10:05,519
I mean, I got far more sleep than Hai Guai.

151
00:10:05,519 --> 00:10:08,480
But it was still only about eight hours in total.

152
00:10:12,679 --> 00:10:15,240
Kyle, you've worked hard.

153
00:10:18,120 --> 00:10:19,720
Bai Rui has a long stride.

154
00:10:20,039 --> 00:10:22,039
I have to run while he's just walking.

155
00:10:22,480 --> 00:10:23,279
Really.

156
00:10:24,320 --> 00:10:25,240
I mostly felt fine.

157
00:10:25,240 --> 00:10:26,120
There was one point

158
00:10:26,120 --> 00:10:29,039
when I hit some kind of limit

159
00:10:29,039 --> 00:10:30,440
from not getting enough sleep.

160
00:10:30,840 --> 00:10:33,480
But after that, I managed it pretty well.

161
00:10:33,480 --> 00:10:34,080
And I realized

162
00:10:34,080 --> 00:10:37,080
that sometimes an hour of sleep is enough,

163
00:10:37,080 --> 00:10:38,120
and then you can keep going.

164
00:11:04,039 --> 00:11:06,039
Bai Rui and I were both exhausted.

165
00:11:06,320 --> 00:11:07,320
And on that mountain,

166
00:11:07,320 --> 00:11:08,960
it felt like we were just zigzagging forever.

167
00:11:10,519 --> 00:11:11,200
The switchbacks

168
00:11:11,200 --> 00:11:11,879
were gentle,

169
00:11:11,879 --> 00:11:14,960
but then we got frustrated

170
00:11:14,960 --> 00:11:16,080
and started climbing straight up.

171
00:11:18,200 --> 00:11:20,879
I felt completely blown up.

172
00:11:21,320 --> 00:11:22,759
Two three-kilometer climbs.

173
00:11:23,240 --> 00:11:24,320
The first one was hard.

174
00:11:24,320 --> 00:11:25,759
The second one was even harder.

175
00:11:32,399 --> 00:11:36,240
The only times I really wanted it to end

176
00:11:36,240 --> 00:11:39,120
or really wanted to reach the next aid station

177
00:11:39,120 --> 00:11:42,600
were on some of the really long downhills.

178
00:11:43,000 --> 00:11:44,519
There were some downhill sections

179
00:11:44,519 --> 00:11:45,759
that were just

180
00:11:47,679 --> 00:11:49,799
painful, and I mean,

181
00:11:49,799 --> 00:11:50,279
that's why,

182
00:11:50,279 --> 00:11:52,840
my quads seized up at the end.

183
00:12:01,480 --> 00:12:03,159
But other than that,

184
00:12:03,159 --> 00:12:04,720
going up the mountains,

185
00:12:04,720 --> 00:12:08,519
I never really felt like I wanted it to end.

186
00:12:08,519 --> 00:12:09,440
If anything,

187
00:12:09,440 --> 00:12:10,759
I just wanted to keep going.

188
00:12:10,759 --> 00:12:13,759
Keep climbing, even on the last ascent.

189
00:12:13,759 --> 00:12:15,600
I think we were both wrecked,

190
00:12:15,600 --> 00:12:17,799
but Hai Guai still looked pretty lively.

191
00:12:20,480 --> 00:12:21,639
What about at night?

192
00:12:21,679 --> 00:12:22,480
At night,

193
00:12:23,440 --> 00:12:24,240
uh...

194
00:12:25,120 --> 00:12:26,120
it was miserable.

195
00:12:26,799 --> 00:12:27,879
Especially on the last mountain.

196
00:12:27,879 --> 00:12:28,759
After we climbed it,

197
00:12:28,759 --> 00:12:30,200
we sat at the saddle in a daze.

198
00:12:31,639 --> 00:12:32,679
We watched the sunrise,

199
00:12:32,679 --> 00:12:34,320
and then forced ourselves to keep going.

200
00:12:35,320 --> 00:12:36,120
Uh, I...

201
00:12:36,120 --> 00:12:37,200
Honestly, the fact that

202
00:12:37,200 --> 00:12:39,600
we made it this far together

203
00:12:40,039 --> 00:12:41,320
already surprised me.

204
00:12:42,600 --> 00:12:44,039
Because he was still in great shape,

205
00:12:44,039 --> 00:12:46,320
and my mind was basically blank.

206
00:12:46,639 --> 00:12:47,399
I was just

207
00:12:47,399 --> 00:12:48,240
putting one foot in front of the other.

208
00:12:51,519 --> 00:12:53,080
Don't think about what's behind you.

209
00:12:53,080 --> 00:12:56,120
Harder things are still waiting ahead.

210
00:12:57,600 --> 00:12:58,200
Bravo.

211
00:12:58,480 --> 00:12:59,320
Thank you.

212
00:13:02,120 --> 00:13:02,960
Thank you.

213
00:13:08,399 --> 00:13:09,919
I didn't feel like I was back on earth.

214
00:13:09,919 --> 00:13:11,759
Because I was heading back into the mountains later.

215
00:13:12,919 --> 00:13:15,879
Only getting back to Courmayeur feels like returning to earth.

216
00:13:18,679 --> 00:13:19,919
It felt so familiar,

217
00:13:20,279 --> 00:13:24,320
because it's what Hai Guai and I used to do.

218
00:13:24,720 --> 00:13:26,679
Not for many years, of course,

219
00:13:26,720 --> 00:13:29,399
I've seen Hai Guai a few times over the last few years,

220
00:13:29,399 --> 00:13:32,080
but only for fairly short runs.

221
00:13:32,080 --> 00:13:32,679
But yeah,

222
00:13:32,679 --> 00:13:34,279
three, four, five years ago,

223
00:13:34,279 --> 00:13:38,039
we did long runs together and built that connection.

224
00:13:38,039 --> 00:13:40,200
I don't quite know how to describe it,

225
00:13:40,200 --> 00:13:42,240
but it's some kind of bond,

226
00:13:42,240 --> 00:13:44,320
moving forward together,

227
00:13:44,320 --> 00:13:46,120
taking on something big together.

228
00:13:46,120 --> 00:13:48,320
It felt like we were right back there.

229
00:13:48,600 --> 00:13:49,960
Even after three or four years

230
00:13:49,960 --> 00:13:52,000
of not doing that.

231
00:13:52,000 --> 00:13:54,840
Yeah, I mean, we talked as well,

232
00:13:54,840 --> 00:13:58,200
but a lot of the time we were just moving together.

233
00:13:58,360 --> 00:14:00,480
If you're really tired when you get to Donnas,

234
00:14:00,480 --> 00:14:02,799
you can rest there for a long time.

235
00:14:02,879 --> 00:14:05,200
I was thinking we shouldn't blow ourselves up.

236
00:14:10,120 --> 00:14:11,120
And in that rhythm,

237
00:14:11,120 --> 00:14:13,440
you develop a kind of synchronization.

238
00:14:13,440 --> 00:14:15,559
We'd want to drink water

239
00:14:15,559 --> 00:14:18,320
or eat at the same time.

240
00:14:18,320 --> 00:14:20,440
It's a fascinating connection.

241
00:14:32,960 --> 00:14:34,440
There can be long stretches of silence.

242
00:14:34,720 --> 00:14:36,919
That kind of unspoken understanding is amazing.

243
00:14:36,919 --> 00:14:38,799
Even when you don't talk,

244
00:14:38,960 --> 00:14:40,440
you can still feel each other.

245
00:14:40,559 --> 00:14:41,960
Like you're doing the same thing together.

246
00:14:47,120 --> 00:14:49,840
You can almost sense what the other person is thinking.

247
00:14:50,120 --> 00:14:51,720
Sometimes you don't want to say anything,

248
00:14:51,720 --> 00:14:53,559
or something suddenly occurs to you.

249
00:14:53,559 --> 00:14:55,320
I've always been curious about that,

250
00:14:55,559 --> 00:14:57,519
and it just happens to be one of his strengths.

251
00:14:57,519 --> 00:14:58,440
At moments like that,

252
00:14:58,440 --> 00:15:00,200
we talk it through.

253
00:15:03,679 --> 00:15:04,600
Time to rest.

254
00:15:04,960 --> 00:15:06,919
Yeah, let's take a nap.

255
00:15:09,679 --> 00:15:12,039
Finally, I can sleep.

256
00:15:12,120 --> 00:15:12,919
Finally.

257
00:15:12,919 --> 00:15:14,600
Oh my God.

258
00:15:16,200 --> 00:15:19,120
I've been out on the course for almost thirty hours.

259
00:15:23,000 --> 00:15:25,279
Can we sleep now?

260
00:15:25,639 --> 00:15:26,960
I'll sleep first.

261
00:15:26,960 --> 00:15:29,679
I can't hold on anymore. I'm so sleepy.

262
00:15:29,679 --> 00:15:30,360
I'm going to sleep.

263
00:15:45,759 --> 00:15:46,440
Yeah, I guess

264
00:15:46,440 --> 00:15:49,480
I kind of lost track of time,

265
00:15:49,480 --> 00:15:51,960
because I didn't have a regular sleep pattern.

266
00:15:52,720 --> 00:15:59,120
But you could still feel the rhythms of the day.

267
00:15:59,799 --> 00:16:02,759
And I guess the difference from normal life is

268
00:16:02,759 --> 00:16:05,879
that those rhythms are defined by nature,

269
00:16:05,879 --> 00:16:06,919
by the sun and the moon,

270
00:16:06,919 --> 00:16:08,759
not by the rhythms

271
00:16:08,759 --> 00:16:10,720
of human schedules and routines.

272
00:16:11,440 --> 00:16:13,799
So for me,

273
00:16:14,799 --> 00:16:15,679
in some ways,

274
00:16:15,679 --> 00:16:17,919
I preferred running at night,

275
00:16:18,320 --> 00:16:21,879
because it was really peaceful.

276
00:16:21,919 --> 00:16:24,639
There were fewer people around,

277
00:16:25,240 --> 00:16:28,919
and almost less to think about.

278
00:16:28,919 --> 00:16:30,879
Because it wasn't sunny

279
00:16:30,879 --> 00:16:31,879
and it wasn't hot.

280
00:16:32,279 --> 00:16:34,000
You could just,

281
00:16:34,000 --> 00:16:34,919
you just had to keep warm.

282
00:16:34,919 --> 00:16:36,120
In some places, anyway.

283
00:16:36,120 --> 00:16:36,799
But that's easy.

284
00:16:36,799 --> 00:16:38,519
You just put on more layers

285
00:16:38,519 --> 00:16:39,480
and keep going.

286
00:16:39,480 --> 00:16:43,399
So I quite liked getting long sections done at night.

287
00:16:45,320 --> 00:16:47,919
And it's just easier to focus at night.

288
00:16:48,120 --> 00:16:50,320
And you also know that if you're starting to feel tired,

289
00:16:50,320 --> 00:16:52,639
or whatever, you know that in a few hours,

290
00:16:52,639 --> 00:16:53,919
the sun will start coming up,

291
00:16:53,919 --> 00:16:57,399
and it's so beautiful that all your energy comes back.

292
00:17:11,440 --> 00:17:12,960
He comes alive at night.

293
00:17:12,960 --> 00:17:15,880
I think he's going to tear me apart. Let's go.

294
00:17:15,920 --> 00:17:17,640
Let's go.

295
00:17:27,720 --> 00:17:28,720
Oh my god.

296
00:17:29,519 --> 00:17:30,519
This trail...

297
00:17:32,960 --> 00:17:33,920
It's indescribable.

298
00:17:36,839 --> 00:17:38,519
Hai Guai said it was indescribable.

299
00:17:38,799 --> 00:17:40,440
I think he was just too tired,

300
00:17:41,000 --> 00:17:42,680
so tired that even the wind felt like a burden.

301
00:17:43,680 --> 00:17:45,440
But when they saw the mountains

302
00:17:45,480 --> 00:17:46,319
and the clouds,

303
00:17:47,000 --> 00:17:48,920
their eyes lit up again.

304
00:17:49,720 --> 00:17:52,359
People who spend time outdoors know that feeling:

305
00:17:52,720 --> 00:17:54,039
your body is in hell,

306
00:17:54,279 --> 00:17:55,440
but your eyes are in heaven.

307
00:17:56,359 --> 00:17:57,359
And time

308
00:17:57,720 --> 00:17:59,039
is always contradictory.

309
00:17:59,680 --> 00:18:00,920
They want it to go faster

310
00:18:01,200 --> 00:18:02,839
so they can get it over with,

311
00:18:03,720 --> 00:18:05,039
but they also want it to slow down,

312
00:18:05,519 --> 00:18:08,319
because they don't want to fast-forward through the scenery.

313
00:18:37,279 --> 00:18:38,240
You really know how to pick a spot.

314
00:18:38,960 --> 00:18:40,599
The prettiest internet-famous hut.

315
00:18:44,079 --> 00:18:46,440
On either side of every saddle,

316
00:18:46,440 --> 00:18:48,119
the temperature

317
00:18:48,119 --> 00:18:49,319
can be completely different.

318
00:18:49,559 --> 00:18:51,279
So when you come out of the forest

319
00:18:51,279 --> 00:18:53,119
and see the meadow or the boulder field,

320
00:18:53,119 --> 00:18:55,720
your spirits lift,

321
00:18:55,720 --> 00:18:57,640
and the fatigue eases a little.

322
00:18:57,640 --> 00:19:00,880
Every stretch around a summit is the essence of it.

323
00:19:14,960 --> 00:19:16,640
I don't know. It's really hard to comprehend

324
00:19:16,640 --> 00:19:19,920
before you've done a race like this.

325
00:19:19,920 --> 00:19:22,559
It's basically one huge climb,

326
00:19:22,559 --> 00:19:24,119
because I slept in Donnas

327
00:19:25,720 --> 00:19:28,559
and then left at around

328
00:19:28,559 --> 00:19:29,680
eleven-thirty or midnight.

329
00:19:30,480 --> 00:19:34,559
There's basically a 2,400-meter climb.

330
00:19:36,519 --> 00:19:39,839
But one thing that surprised me was

331
00:19:39,839 --> 00:19:43,279
that even with all the ups and downs,

332
00:19:43,279 --> 00:19:44,319
in some ways

333
00:19:44,319 --> 00:19:47,240
you actually feel stronger as the race goes on.

334
00:19:47,640 --> 00:19:49,240
It sounds strange to say that because obviously

335
00:19:49,240 --> 00:19:51,480
I slowed down, and by the end

336
00:19:51,480 --> 00:19:54,200
my quads were kind of injured, not really injured,

337
00:19:54,200 --> 00:19:56,640
but overused and swollen.

338
00:19:58,119 --> 00:20:01,119
But even so, on the final climb,

339
00:20:01,119 --> 00:20:02,519
I felt strong,

340
00:20:02,519 --> 00:20:04,920
I felt stronger on the last hill

341
00:20:04,920 --> 00:20:06,039
than I did on the first few.

342
00:20:06,039 --> 00:20:08,079
I felt like I'd adapted.

343
00:20:11,039 --> 00:20:15,240
The other thing I was thinking about a lot,

344
00:20:15,240 --> 00:20:17,480
whenever my brain was still awake

345
00:20:17,480 --> 00:20:18,920
and I wasn't too tired,

346
00:20:19,119 --> 00:20:21,240
was how much I wanted to

347
00:20:21,240 --> 00:20:22,519
come back to this area,

348
00:20:22,519 --> 00:20:25,640
and explore other paths,

349
00:20:25,640 --> 00:20:26,920
just on my own,

350
00:20:26,920 --> 00:20:28,440
outside of a race format.

351
00:20:30,240 --> 00:20:32,119
We crossed so many different trails,

352
00:20:32,119 --> 00:20:33,440
and there are so many beautiful places,

353
00:20:33,440 --> 00:20:35,720
I'd like to come back to new places,

354
00:20:35,720 --> 00:20:36,920
to keep exploring.

355
00:20:42,400 --> 00:20:43,440
Ten years ago,

356
00:20:43,440 --> 00:20:44,880
when I saw others complete the Tor des Géants,

357
00:20:44,880 --> 00:20:47,480
I was still a chubby guy weighing about 85 kilos.

358
00:20:47,480 --> 00:20:50,720
I lost weight, and then I got into the sport.

359
00:20:51,119 --> 00:20:52,880
If you really like it,

360
00:20:52,880 --> 00:20:54,720
and if this film moves you,

361
00:20:54,720 --> 00:20:56,799
or if the scenery in the film

362
00:20:56,799 --> 00:20:57,640
speaks to you,

363
00:20:57,640 --> 00:21:01,799
I think the first thing is just to try.

364
00:21:01,799 --> 00:21:03,400
The path is made one step at a time.

365
00:21:03,400 --> 00:21:04,480
What matters is taking action,

366
00:21:04,480 --> 00:21:07,240
not obsessing over what to choose.

367
00:21:08,119 --> 00:21:09,960
Whether you choose the Tor des Geants

368
00:21:09,960 --> 00:21:12,279
or just go for a hike in a park,

369
00:21:12,279 --> 00:21:15,039
or even leave home and walk down an unfamiliar street,

370
00:21:15,039 --> 00:21:16,519
all of those things are good for you,

371
00:21:16,519 --> 00:21:17,920
as long as you go out and experience them,

372
00:21:17,920 --> 00:21:19,119
keep experiencing different things,

373
00:21:19,319 --> 00:21:20,359
and let them accumulate over time.

374
00:21:20,359 --> 00:21:23,000
I think you'll find your own path.

375
00:21:23,000 --> 00:21:24,920
It's not about finishing the Tor des Geants,

376
00:21:24,920 --> 00:21:26,720
or completing the PTL,

377
00:21:26,720 --> 00:21:28,799
as some ultimate goal.

378
00:21:28,960 --> 00:21:31,240
Don't make other people's goals your own.

379
00:21:31,240 --> 00:21:32,720
Even if you achieve them,

380
00:21:32,720 --> 00:21:35,119
you may not feel that happy.

381
00:21:35,119 --> 00:21:35,720
You may even find

382
00:21:35,720 --> 00:21:38,200
you don't know what to do next.

383
00:21:38,200 --> 00:21:40,480
In the course of your own exploration,

384
00:21:40,480 --> 00:21:41,640
you should have a style of your own.

385
00:21:43,000 --> 00:21:44,920
Don't think that nature

386
00:21:44,920 --> 00:21:47,599
has to mean mountains, seas, lakes, and so on.

387
00:21:47,599 --> 00:21:50,720
In fact, nature can be the city you live in,

388
00:21:50,720 --> 00:21:52,559
or the streets you walk every day.

389
00:21:52,559 --> 00:21:53,480
All of that is nature too.

390
00:21:55,000 --> 00:21:58,519
Don't just

391
00:21:58,519 --> 00:22:01,559
only through social media,

392
00:22:01,559 --> 00:22:02,720
and nature through social media.

393
00:22:02,720 --> 00:22:04,920
I think the best way is to go out and experience it,

394
00:22:04,920 --> 00:22:06,000
and experience more of it.

395
00:22:14,039 --> 00:22:14,839
Yes.

396
00:22:15,680 --> 00:22:16,480
Oh.

397
00:22:17,119 --> 00:22:17,920
Oh.

398
00:22:46,440 --> 00:22:47,839
Back when I first started running,

399
00:22:47,839 --> 00:22:48,799
whether it was a 100-kilometer race

400
00:22:48,799 --> 00:22:50,880
or navigating my own way through Wugong Mountain,

401
00:22:50,880 --> 00:22:52,720
when I was in the forest and hit spider webs,

402
00:22:53,079 --> 00:22:53,960
my energy dropped,

403
00:22:53,960 --> 00:22:55,680
and my face was covered with bugs,

404
00:22:55,680 --> 00:22:57,119
Getting tangled in spider webs was so frustrating.

405
00:22:57,880 --> 00:22:58,720
But that mindset

406
00:22:58,720 --> 00:23:01,119
gradually carried over into

407
00:23:01,119 --> 00:23:02,680
my Tor des Geants today.

408
00:23:02,680 --> 00:23:05,680
When I face darkness, fatigue, or injury,

409
00:23:05,680 --> 00:23:08,440
I have to keep adjusting myself,

410
00:23:08,440 --> 00:23:11,079
find a way to lift my spirits and get to the next aid station.

411
00:23:11,119 --> 00:23:12,319
It should be the process.

412
00:23:13,079 --> 00:23:14,119
All I can say is

413
00:23:14,240 --> 00:23:16,079
the memories this place left me are so beautiful.

414
00:23:16,079 --> 00:23:18,400
This place is truly beautiful.

415
00:23:18,480 --> 00:23:20,839
I'll try to come back every year.

416
00:23:20,839 --> 00:23:23,920
I'll keep training

417
00:23:23,920 --> 00:23:26,119
so that next time the experience can be even better,

418
00:23:26,279 --> 00:23:28,559
not so that I can get a better result.

419
00:23:28,559 --> 00:23:30,000
At the same time,

420
00:23:30,000 --> 00:23:31,799
I may become calmer.

421
00:23:31,799 --> 00:23:33,440
I think that's the goal I'm pursuing.

422
00:23:38,240 --> 00:23:39,960
After work every day,

423
00:23:39,960 --> 00:23:41,640
I run up the hill behind my workplace

424
00:23:41,759 --> 00:23:43,160
and watch the sunset from afar.

425
00:23:43,160 --> 00:23:44,440
I can see Qingshuijian Mountain.

426
00:23:44,440 --> 00:23:45,960
I don't think,

427
00:23:45,960 --> 00:23:47,640
the Alps are all that important.

428
00:23:47,640 --> 00:23:49,119
That's how I feel.

429
00:23:51,359 --> 00:23:53,079
Life is a,

430
00:23:53,079 --> 00:23:53,640
circle.

431
00:23:53,640 --> 00:23:55,920
Some people may draw a big circle

432
00:23:56,079 --> 00:23:57,000
and take many paths.

433
00:23:57,000 --> 00:23:59,079
I might draw a slightly smaller loop.

434
00:23:59,359 --> 00:24:00,319
I think that's enough.

435
00:24:06,680 --> 00:24:08,000
The joy of this,

436
00:24:08,000 --> 00:24:10,440
isn't really about the race.

437
00:24:10,440 --> 00:24:12,920
It's about the feeling and the connection we have,

438
00:24:12,920 --> 00:24:15,720
with the mountains and with nature.

439
00:24:15,720 --> 00:24:17,880
That's really it. Yeah.

440
00:24:17,880 --> 00:24:20,519
So I'd love to come back and feel that again,

441
00:24:20,519 --> 00:24:23,000
either on my own,

442
00:24:23,000 --> 00:24:25,720
or with friends, designing our own routes.

443
00:24:56,559 --> 00:24:59,000
I can't say exactly,

444
00:24:59,720 --> 00:25:02,000
whether there were any big things I was thinking through

445
00:25:02,000 --> 00:25:03,000
while I was climbing.

446
00:25:03,279 --> 00:25:07,599
There are a few things I can remember now,

447
00:25:07,599 --> 00:25:08,839
nothing especially interesting,

448
00:25:08,839 --> 00:25:10,279
but I'll say them anyway.

449
00:25:10,720 --> 00:25:12,960
One thing I noticed,

450
00:25:12,960 --> 00:25:13,839
especially during the day,

451
00:25:15,920 --> 00:25:19,680
was just how many people were out in the mountains.

452
00:25:19,839 --> 00:25:20,640
Older people,

453
00:25:20,640 --> 00:25:22,559
young people, children, families,

454
00:25:22,559 --> 00:25:24,519
hiking, running, all of it.

455
00:25:24,519 --> 00:25:25,279
I just thought, wow,

456
00:25:25,279 --> 00:25:28,960
the outdoor culture here is so rich. It's really impressive.

457
00:25:30,960 --> 00:25:32,839
So the title of this film,

458
00:25:32,839 --> 00:25:34,799
Ephemeral Mountains,

459
00:25:34,799 --> 00:25:36,119
what does that mean to you?

460
00:25:36,960 --> 00:25:38,000
Ephemeral?

461
00:25:38,279 --> 00:25:40,559
As in "Ephemeral Mountains"?

462
00:25:41,559 --> 00:25:43,400
I don't really buy that.

463
00:25:43,680 --> 00:25:45,640
I don't feel anything ephemeral right now,

464
00:25:45,640 --> 00:25:48,680
because they're hitting me in the face every day.

465
00:25:49,720 --> 00:25:51,200
It feels very, very real,

466
00:25:51,200 --> 00:25:52,240
and very hard.

467
00:25:54,880 --> 00:25:57,839
Obviously, if you train really hard,

468
00:25:57,839 --> 00:26:00,279
like Hai Guai does.

469
00:26:00,279 --> 00:26:02,720
But as I said before, for Hai Guai,

470
00:26:02,720 --> 00:26:04,680
I don't even think of it as training, exactly.

471
00:26:04,680 --> 00:26:08,400
It's not like he follows some training calendar.

472
00:26:09,279 --> 00:26:10,400
That's just what he does.

473
00:26:10,720 --> 00:26:11,079
But, you know,

474
00:26:11,079 --> 00:26:12,920
he spends a lot of time in the mountains,

475
00:26:12,920 --> 00:26:14,599
and that naturally makes you faster.

476
00:26:15,039 --> 00:26:17,440
But I think the core skill here,

477
00:26:17,440 --> 00:26:20,839
is really understanding your body.

478
00:26:20,839 --> 00:26:24,880
If you know how much water, salt, and food

479
00:26:26,000 --> 00:26:26,960
your body needs,

480
00:26:26,960 --> 00:26:30,119
and you can actually digest it properly,

481
00:26:30,119 --> 00:26:32,400
then you can just keep going. Sleep matters too,

482
00:26:32,400 --> 00:26:34,599
and that's the part I struggle with.

483
00:26:41,640 --> 00:26:43,960
I never really wanted it to end.

484
00:26:43,960 --> 00:26:45,720
I just wanted to keep going,

485
00:26:45,720 --> 00:26:48,960
keep climbing, even on that last climb.

486
00:26:50,279 --> 00:26:51,880
I felt full of energy.

487
00:26:51,880 --> 00:26:53,400
Honestly, I would've been happy

488
00:26:53,400 --> 00:26:55,799
if that climb had gone on for another thousand meters.

489
00:26:57,839 --> 00:26:59,720
You're still smiling.

490
00:27:01,559 --> 00:27:06,279
I don't know, it just feels good. And the views are amazing.

491
00:27:06,279 --> 00:27:08,079
It's not just the view from the top,

492
00:27:08,079 --> 00:27:11,039
it's the view every hundred meters.

493
00:27:11,039 --> 00:27:13,240
Every few hundred meters, it's different.

494
00:27:13,240 --> 00:27:15,079
I'd been waiting for it for

495
00:27:15,079 --> 00:27:17,160
all 330 kilometers, and honestly,

496
00:27:17,160 --> 00:27:21,480
when I reached the last pass,

497
00:27:22,200 --> 00:27:25,000
I was sad it was the last one.

498
00:27:25,279 --> 00:27:27,160
I didn't want it to be the last.

499
00:27:27,160 --> 00:27:29,359
It's strange to think that was the final climb.

500
00:27:35,880 --> 00:27:38,240
And it feels really special.

501
00:27:38,640 --> 00:27:42,440
And I guess when I get back to normal life,

502
00:27:42,480 --> 00:27:47,559
I'm going to miss that feeling of

503
00:27:49,359 --> 00:27:50,319
pushing my body,

504
00:27:50,319 --> 00:27:52,319
and feeling that connection with nature.

505
00:27:58,359 --> 00:28:00,240
Okay, thank you.

506
00:28:05,480 --> 00:28:09,200
If you want something hot, soup, tea, coffee...

507
00:28:09,200 --> 00:28:10,079
Okay.

508
00:28:11,480 --> 00:28:12,839
What would you like?

509
00:28:14,400 --> 00:28:15,200
Okay.

510
00:28:16,799 --> 00:28:19,200
Perfect, thank you. Bye.

511
00:28:19,200 --> 00:28:21,599
Thank you too.

512
00:28:26,839 --> 00:28:28,319
It's ephemeral.

513
00:28:28,319 --> 00:28:30,119
I can really feel that now.

514
00:28:30,359 --> 00:28:32,240
It feels like a long time while you're inside it.

515
00:28:32,240 --> 00:28:33,960
Even after the first night,

516
00:28:33,960 --> 00:28:36,279
I felt like I couldn't even imagine

517
00:28:36,279 --> 00:28:37,319
there were still three days left.

518
00:28:37,960 --> 00:28:40,400
But the moment you stop thinking about it,

519
00:28:40,400 --> 00:28:41,440
you can hardly feel it at all.

520
00:28:41,440 --> 00:28:43,720
You just keep moving, and suddenly it's over.

521
00:28:49,119 --> 00:28:50,519
After climbing so many mountains,

522
00:28:50,880 --> 00:28:52,400
do you still like climbing?

523
00:28:52,400 --> 00:28:53,200
Of course.

524
00:28:53,200 --> 00:28:55,599
I'm already looking forward to the next one.

525
00:29:02,079 --> 00:29:03,039
After climbing that many mountains,

526
00:29:03,519 --> 00:29:05,440
I still don't feel tired of climbing.

527
00:29:07,960 --> 00:29:08,920
Today was so long.

528
00:29:09,519 --> 00:29:10,640
I feel like I've been climbing forever.

529
00:29:13,200 --> 00:29:15,119
All that pain is just your brain talking.

530
00:29:15,119 --> 00:29:19,279
It's lying to you. It wants you back in the car.

531
00:29:21,359 --> 00:29:22,680
Maybe that moment is right now.

532
00:29:22,680 --> 00:29:24,119
I feel like I've only done one thing.

533
00:29:24,119 --> 00:29:24,799
That's all.

534
00:29:24,799 --> 00:29:25,839
But as for

535
00:29:25,839 --> 00:29:26,599
what it might mean,

536
00:29:26,599 --> 00:29:29,799
for my life in the future,

537
00:29:29,799 --> 00:29:30,640
maybe

538
00:29:30,839 --> 00:29:34,200
I'll only know when it happens.

539
00:29:37,559 --> 00:29:38,240
But for now,

540
00:29:38,240 --> 00:29:40,680
I don't think about it much.

541
00:29:40,920 --> 00:29:44,279
I don't think finishing this matters that much,

542
00:29:44,279 --> 00:29:45,359
or that it's something incredible.

543
00:29:45,359 --> 00:29:46,759
It's over now.

544
00:29:51,240 --> 00:29:54,200
A man with thunder in his chest and a calm face

545
00:29:55,000 --> 00:29:56,119
is fit to be a general.

546
00:29:56,319 --> 00:29:57,920
Right now, I'm all thunder inside,

547
00:29:58,519 --> 00:29:59,720
because the soles of my feet...

548
00:30:01,039 --> 00:30:02,640
it hurts like hell to walk on this road.

549
00:30:04,240 --> 00:30:05,279
Hai Guai and Bai Rui

550
00:30:05,279 --> 00:30:07,200
have finally completed their journey of giants.

551
00:30:07,920 --> 00:30:09,039
For us,

552
00:30:09,039 --> 00:30:10,200
the Alps are too far away,

553
00:30:10,599 --> 00:30:12,000
and 330 kilometers feels impossible.

554
00:30:12,880 --> 00:30:14,720
But the moment you step outside,

555
00:30:15,200 --> 00:30:17,039
nature is already right beside you.

556
00:30:48,839 --> 00:30:51,279
When you really come back, this is what it looks like.

557
00:30:51,279 --> 00:30:52,000
Maybe out there,

558
00:30:52,000 --> 00:30:54,160
you imagined it countless times.

559
00:30:54,160 --> 00:30:55,359
I've imagined it countless times.

560
00:30:55,359 --> 00:30:58,640
That breakfast we had this morning,

561
00:31:01,519 --> 00:31:03,279
was the happiest moment.

562
00:31:03,279 --> 00:31:04,640
Maybe the happiest of the year.

563
00:31:04,640 --> 00:31:05,839
Happier than Spring Festival.

564
00:31:07,480 --> 00:31:08,839
How did you get up here?

565
00:31:09,960 --> 00:31:11,200
Can you drive halfway up?

566
00:31:11,200 --> 00:31:11,960
No, you can't.

567
00:31:11,960 --> 00:31:12,599
Oh my.

568
00:31:12,880 --> 00:31:13,680
We climbed all the way up here.

569
00:31:17,880 --> 00:31:18,960
You're the man, Director Jia.

570
00:31:27,640 --> 00:31:28,599
Call Xiaoqin.

571
00:31:28,759 --> 00:31:29,559
Call Xiaoqin.

572
00:31:42,559 --> 00:31:43,359
Here she comes.

573
00:31:49,839 --> 00:31:51,240
You're the best.
